  "chunk_index": 34,
  "summary": "Jason Radle and Ella Jelinsky discuss the nature of happiness, with Jason noting that Marina Gregg was like a child when content. Ella expresses cynicism regarding lasting happiness and mentions that Giuseppe has traveled to London to visit a sick relative in Soho. Following the conversation, Ella leaves the office to retrieve nasal spray for her hay fever. While in her bathroom, she uses a spray bottle but realizes too late that the liquid has a bitter almond taste, indicating she has inhaled cyanide.\n\nIn a separate investigation, Frank Koenig informs Clutter that Miss Bristow was not in London on the day in question. Clutter and Koenig discuss the possibility that the butler, who is also in London, could have slipped cyanide into Eileen's inhaler. Later, Claddock calls Adwick Fenn to report Ella Jelinsky's death by cyanide poisoning. Fenn suggests that Jason Radle might possess information regarding her motives. Fenn then reveals that Ella had previously called him, claiming she saw him put pills in a drink, implying an attempt at blackmail. Fenn identifies the caller as Ella because the voice sneezed, a symptom of her hay fever. Claddock informs Fenn that his whereabouts will be investigated, while Claddock, Clark, and Cuney discuss whether Fenn’s explanation is a \"grand deception\" involving a fake alibi.\n\nMeanwhile, Joseph returns to Gosington Manor after midnight. As he enters his suite and turns the key in the lock, he feels a hard object against his back and is ordered by a voice to raise his hands and remain silent.",
